== Test Design
//Describe your experimental setup including the facilities, equipment, sensors, types of measurements, data acquisition parameters, the data you collect, and any other relevant information to describe the setup of your test. Include photographs, diagrams, and graphics as necessary to clearly describe your setup.

In order to test the MPHX jig's linearity, the jig will be run through the roller and feed system without adhesive at least 20 times. This test will be used to check the number of times the MPHX jig catches on the feed and results in a system failure. We will be checking and recording all failure modes, keeping a total of the frequency of each. After the first set of runs, the feed will be adjusted and the test can be repeated. 

Testing should follow the following procedure:
1. Turn on and set up the roller system without adhesive
2. Place MPHX plates into the MPHX jig
3. Run the system as normal (line up the MPHX jig with the roller system)
4. Wait and check for clear catching of the MPHX jig
5. Record and tally any locations of catching if they occur
6. Iterate at different angles from directly in line (5-15 degrees)
7. Redesign jig if needed
8. Repeat steps 3-7, 20 times
9. Adjust feed alignment as necessary, repeat steps 1-8

== Data Collection
// What variables will be measured (i.e. what specific data and information you will collect), how much data will you collect, and why?

A table of tests values will be recorded keeping track of the catching locations and the total number of times they cause a failure. A failure is classified as any significant disruption to the feed process which might lead to improper glue application or prevention of the jig from advancing.

A new table of test data will be created after every alteration to the feed alignment and changes in dimensions/measurements will be recorded.

== Data Analysis
// How will you evaluate your collected data. You must describe your analyses, provide figures and tables, and describe statistical methods (where appropriate).
The data from this test will allow us to determine and identify the catching locations.The tallies of failures at each across feed adjustments will pinpoint the most consistent modes of failure and causes.

== Safety Considerations
// //Describe any potential safety concerns and risk mitigation strategies  required for your testing. Mitigation strategies may include items such as required personal protective equipment, physical barriers around test equipment, etc.
Because this test does not required the use of adhesives, it can be conducted in any setting. In the event that the jig does catch, it is imperative that the system be switched off to allow time to properly identify the catching location and safely remove the jig from the feed. One should not attempt to remove the jig while the rollers are active.


== Limitations
// //Describe the assumptions and limitations of your tests and what impact this may have on your results
This test is limited by the amount of tests we conduct and the  fact that failures may be successive since one point of catching stops the jig before another point of catching can occur. This prevents us from identifying any successive failure modes. The test is also limited by the possible adjustments we can make to the feed between sets of trial runs. The feed only has a couple of parameters which can be adjusted on the fly, while properties such as the feed inlet angles require more serious modifications to implement. 
